</ul>
<h2 class=3D"template" id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-BusinessRules">Busines=
s Rules</h2>
<ul>
<li>An asset can be managed by multiple companies</li>
<li>A user can belong to only one company</li>
<li>A company can have many users</li>
<li>A system wide role will be setup called administrator, these have acces=
s to everything</li>
<li>A report/dashboard should be available to a limit number of users withi=
n the company</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-Questions">Questions</h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-1.Shouldeachcompanyhaveaccesstoallsensors=
propertiesoftheassetstheyhaveaccessto?">1. Should each company have access =
to all sensors properties of the assets they have access to?</h3>
<p>Yes, no individual access required</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-2.Cantheassettypeofanassetbechanged?">2. =
Can the assettype of an asset be changed?</h3>
<p>We should take version control into account here. What if we want to upg=
rade an asset to a new version? Should the assettype change?&nbsp;<u><stron=
g>Define assetType</strong></u>.</p>
<p>Notes: Perhaps we should just create a new asset, since properties may h=
ave changed between versions? TBD</p>
<p>Notes: We want to retain the data for the old asset, but we won't be abl=
e to use it anymore for reporting on the new asset</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-3.Canastaticproperty,aftercreating,stillb=
echanged/deleted?">3. Can a static property, after creating, still be chang=
ed/deleted?</h3>
<p>No, once created, the property can no longer be changed/deleted. The val=
ue a certain asset has for this property can however still change.&nbsp;</p=
>
<h3 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-4.Shouldstaticpropertiesbesecuredonacompa=
nylevel?">4. Should static properties be secured on a company level?</h3>
<p>Every company has access to all the properties as long as they have acce=
ss to the asset.</p>
<p>Example: Company A adds property K to assettype X, should company B who =
also sees assettype X be allowed to view &amp; add values of property K?</p=
>
<p>Answer: Yes.<br><strong>Proposed solution</strong></p>
<p><s>Define different types of static properties:</s></p>
<ul>
<li><s><strong>private get/private set&nbsp;</strong>static property =E2=86=
=92 only visible/editable to own company</s></li>
<li><s><strong>public get/private set&nbsp;</strong>static property =E2=86=
=92 only editable by own company, viewable by other companies</s></li>
<li><s><strong>public get/public set&nbsp;</strong>static property =E2=86=
=92 visible/editable by all companies</s></li>
</ul>
<p><s>editable: change value, change property definition?</s></p>
<p><s>viewable: see the property in the dashboard/report/etc...</s></p>
<p><s>static properties are always optional as we may not always know the c=
orrect value (i.e. across companies)</s></p>
<p>Resolution: Not (yet) necessary</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-6.1.4SecurityArchive-5.Howisthepropertysecurityacrosscompanies=
defined?">5. How is the property security across companies defined?</h3>
<p>Conclusion: Not (yet) necessary</p>
<p><s>Example:&nbsp;<strong>The Battle Of The Properties</strong>. A bus is=
 manufactered by company X and has a battery manufactured by company Y. The=
 bus has a property Battery_Health which is important for company Y. Who de=
cides whether company X or company Y can view this property?</s></p>
